94-09 and 94-15 159th Street, at and adjoining the S.E. corner of Beaver Road, just below the Long lIsland Railroad tracks, showing two old frame houses of eighteanth century con-struction. Aoross the roof is St. Monicas Roman Catholic Church on 160th Street; on the right is St. Monica's Hall. 159th Street was known as Prospect Street and Medford Street. Beaver Road, at
this point, has not yet been cut through.
P. L. Sperr  March 30, 1932

94-27 159th Street, east side, south of Beaver Road, showing St. Monicas Hall, belonging to St. Monicas Roman Catholic Church which fronts on 160th Street. The congregationsocial activities are conducted here.

P. L. Sperr
March 30, 1932

160th Street, west side, between Beaver Road and Dale Road, showing St. Monicas Roman Catholic Church and parsonage, viewed southwestward from the Long Island Railroad tracks. View 2 shows the rear of the church, on 159th Street.
